 &nbsp;The `chord` and `melody` sections contain the result of the automatic extraction according to each algorithm. 

 The `sandbox` section contains the original data from the source dataset (Rondo DB), with the addition of the `claraprints` section with various claraprints for different durations and algorithms. For example, `30s_chords_chordino` is the claraprint for the 30 first seconds of this recording using the Chordino algorithm. 

 The original versions of the sandox data are described on  https://www.rondodb.com/about  and are copied below: 

 This dataset contains 100 of such works. Here are a detailed field description: 
&bull;  rdb_id_piece  (100/100): This is the unique piece ID of this work in Rondo DB. If you prefix it with https://www.rondodb.com/piece/ you will reach its official page on Rondo DB. 
&bull;  name  (100/100): The raw name of the piece. As most of classical pieces don&#39;t have titles, this is in general the form of the piece, like here: &quot;Symphony&quot;. 
&bull;  number  (37/100): Applicable to pieces with numbering. Only 32 of them in this dataset. Otherwise the field is absent. 
&bull;  piece_full_name  (100/100): Generally accepted name for the given piece. Contains catalog information, subname and tonality. 
&bull;  piece_full_name_with_composer  (100/100): Same as  piece_full_name  but prefixed with composer first name and last name and a semi column. 
&bull;  catalog_number  (79/100): This is the full information of how this piece is generally catalogued. Despite the name of the field, this is not a number but a textual information, such as &quot;Op. 37&quot; 
&bull;  tonality  (57/100): A full tonality (key and mode) of the given piece. Flats and sharps are writen like &quot;E-flat&quot; or &quot;C-sharp&quot;. 
&bull;  composition_year  (91/100): The year on four digit of the composition of this piece. 
&bull;  wikipedia_url  (82/100): The full URL of the English Wikipedia page describing this work. 
&bull;  rdb_id_movement  (26/100): The ID of a movement on Rondo DB. By prefixing this ID with URL https://www.rondodb.com/movement/ you will go to the unique movement page on Rondo DB. A &quot;movement&quot; can also be a &quot;part&quot; in a piece edited with several parts, like a book of preludes, &eacute;tudes, or arias in an opera. 
&bull;  movement_full_name  (26/100): The name of a movement, which can contain the number of the movement, like in &quot;5. Andaluza&quot;. The movement name is part of the  piece_full_name  and  piece_full_name_with_composer  as described above. 
 composer  (100/100) is a nested object and contains the following fields: 
&bull;  rdb_id_people  (100/100): The Rondo DB ID of this composer. By prefixing this ID with URL https://www.rondodb.com/people/ you will go to the unique composer page on Rondo DB. 
&bull;  birth_date  (100/100): The date of birth in format YYYY-MM-DD. 
&bull;  death_date  (100/100): The date of death in format YYYY-MM-DD. 
&bull;  name  (100/100): The full name of the composer like &quot;Heitor Villa-Lobos&quot;. 
 recordings  (100/100) contains a like of five recording objects. Each recording contains the following fields: 
&bull;  is_live  (500/500) indicates if the recording has been performed live or not. When recorded live, it indicates that it  can  contain applauses before/after the recording, tuning orchestra, noises during the performances... 
&bull;  start_at  (500/500) the time where the piece is actually starting at, in seconds. Will roughly starts in less than a second after this point. The instruction given to the annotator was: &quot;place the cursor  just before  the piece actually starts&quot;. 
&bull;  url  (500/500) the full URL of the Youtube video. At the time of the creation of the dataset, all recording were publicly available.

